tool.name: GenerateHeatPlot

param.name: wq_var
param.expression: temp | ph | sp_cond | salinity | dissolved_oxygen | dissolved_oxygen_percent | dep_25 | par | rpar | turbidity_sc | chl | chl_corrected | m_value
param.dialogReference:
The water quality variable(s) to create plots for:

  • Temperature

  • pH

  • Conductivity

  • Salinity

  • Dissolved Oxygen

  • Dissolved Oxygen (%)

  • Depth (meters) - dep_25

  • PAR

  • RPAR

  • Turbidity

  • Chlorophyll

  • Chlorophyll - corrected using linear model from the vertical gains and lab samples

param.name: output
param.dialogReference:
Custom title for the graph to override the default title.

The default title for the graph is the site code and the water quality varible. Example: "CA - PH"

Note: providing a custom title will be applied for all the graphs when multiple water quality parameters are selected

param.name: output_folder
param.dialogReference:
Location to save the graphs as PNGs

Files will be saved using the site code and water quality variable to build the filename (ie ca_ph.png)

tool.summary:
Generate a water quality "heatplot" showing how a varible changes along the transect over time.

The x-axis represents each month and the y-axis is the distance (km) along the transect. Only water quality records that have an XY location and are able to be linear referenced (m_value) are included in the plot.

The tool works by passing the parameters to a R script (via subprocess) that queries the database for all the water quality records on the selected transect and uses ggplot to make the heatplot by symbolizing by the water quality variable.
